## Common Pitfalls to Avoid
- **Look-ahead bias**: Signal at candle N can ONLY use data from candles 0 to N-1. Check every calculation.
- **Survivorship bias**: Include periods when your strategy would have been halted by circuit breakers
- **Ignoring fees**: Always model Kalshi fees — they significantly impact short-term strategies
- **Peeking at test set**: Once you've looked at test data to "just check something," it's no longer out-of-sample
- **Too few trades**: < 200 trades means results are noise — get more data or loosen entry criteria slightly
- **Unrealistic fills**: Assume you get fills at slight slippage from mid — not always at best price

